\title{L'Hôpital's rule Proof (with $\frac{0}{0}$ only)}
\author{Jeremy Chow}
\date{12/18/18}

\begin{document}
\maketitle
L'Hôpital's rule stated that if $\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}$ is indeterminate, and both functions can be differentiated at $x=a$, then $\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}=\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}$. In this proof we are only going to explore the case where the limit becomes $\frac{0}{0}$. Given that the limit will turn into $\frac{0}{0}$, it can be implied that $\lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)=0$ and $\lim\limits_{x\to a} g(x)=0$, and since differentiability implied continuity, $f(a)=g(a)=0$. Therefore\\$\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\\=\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)-0}{g(x)-0}\\=\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{g(x)-g(a)}\\=\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}}{\frac{g(x)-g(a)}{x-a}}\\=\frac{f'(a)}{g'(a)}\\=\lim\limits_{x\to a}\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}\\$QED
\end{document}